-- South Korean Stocks Advance on U.S. Jobs, Factory Data; Hanjin Heavy Jumps
-- B y   S a e r o m i   S h i n
-- 2011-02-07T07:17:47Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-07/south-korean-stocks-advance-most-in-two-months-after-better-u-s-jobs-data.html
South Korean stocks advanced after
the Lunar New Year holidays, on speculation exports will gain as
U.S. jobs and manufacturing data improved.    Hyundai Motor Co .,  South Korea ’s largest automaker, climbed
2.2 percent after saying U.S. sales jumped. Hanjin Heavy
Industries & Construction Co., a shipyard, surged 8.4 percent
after Samsung Securities Co. raised its stock rating. Samsung
Engineering Co., the nation’s biggest engineering company,
increased 1 percent after winning a $550 million order.  The  Kospi Index  rose 0.5 percent to 2,081.74 as of the 3
p.m. close on the Korea Exchange. The nation’s financial markets
were closed between Feb. 2 and Feb. 4, during which the MSCI
Asia Pacific Index climbed 1.5 percent. The won strengthened 0.9
percent to 1,107.50 per dollar at the 3 p.m. close in Seoul,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  “We’re seeing more positive signs of the  U.S. economy 
embarking on a recovery track,” said Im Jeong Jae, a  fund
manager  in Seoul at Shinhan BNP Paribas Asset Management Co.,
which oversees $29 billion of assets. “Investors are trying to
keep up with gains seen in the region during Korea’s break.”  The U.S. unemployment rate fell to 9 percent in January
from 9.4 percent in December, the Labor Department said Feb. 4.
Economists surveyed by Bloomberg had expected an increase to 9.5
percent.  U.S. Manufacturing  U.S. manufacturing unexpectedly accelerated in January at
the fastest pace in more than six years, figures from the Tempe,
Arizona-based Institute for Supply Management showed Feb. 1. The
factory index rose to 60.8, beating the median economist
projection of 58. Readings greater than 50 signal growth.  European manufacturing gained at the quickest rate in nine
months and U.K. production increased at a record pace in January,
separate data showed last week. In  China , a purchasing managers’
index exceeded the 50 level that divides expansion and
contraction.  Hyundai Motor rose 2.2 percent to 185,000 won after its U.S.
sales rose 22 percent to 37,214 vehicles last month. Gains were
led by the Sonata sedan and included 254 units of the new Equus
luxury sedan, the Seoul-based company’s most expensive U.S.
model ever, with a $58,000 base price. Affiliate  Kia Motors
Corp ., which reported a 26 percent gain in U.S. sales to 27,789,
climbed 4 percent to 57,400 won.    Hyundai Mobis   Hyundai Mobis Co., the nation’s biggest auto-parts maker,
advanced 2.3 percent to 267,000 won.  Hanjin Heavy, which had its stock rating raised by Samsung
Securities to “buy” from “hold,” jumped 8.4 percent to
41,200 won. Samsung Engineering gained 1 percent to 208,000 won
after getting a $550 million order to build and operate a sewage
treatment plant in  Bahrain .  Poongsan Corp., a copper products maker, added 6.1 percent
to 46,000 won, after copper extended a rally to a record on
mounting concern that the global economic recovery will boost
consumption of the metal used in cars, homes and appliances.  Woori Investment & Securities Co. gained 6.3 percent to
22,750 won on speculation the brokerage may be sold separately
when its parent is privatized, said Cho Soung Kyung, an analyst
with KTB Securities Co.  To contact the reporter on this story:
